ODE II.

In as much as the Romans had relaxed the strictness of their discipline, and fallen into luxury and vice, the poet exhorts them to commence a reform by educating their children differently. He intimates that they should early be inured to labor and privation, that, by enduring the hardships of warfare, they may prize the bless- ings of peace and frugality.
